{
  "texts": [
    "If it is reasonable to accept that loneliness is the kind of alienation experience that evolves out of and is an expression of distorted social recognition relations (graspable as a lack of, or a false recognition practice), and social AI is designed to fill precisely this gap of an experienced lack of relatedness or should even compensate for experiences of false recognition, it is fair enough to question whether AICs, no matter how \"sociable\" they appear, can really help to overcome loneliness.",
    "This would imply that lonely people are placed in a relation that basically allows them to feel connected in the first place.",
    "While I believe that AICs can provide this basic feeling of \"connectedness,\" one can doubt whether these devices sufficiently contribute to the kind of social inclusion that people experiencing loneliness really need.",
    "I suspect that we are rather dealing with the digital variant of a fundamental lack of recognition in human-AI companionship, albeit with AICs delivering the perfect illusion of recognition.",
    "Ergo there might be the concern that AICs contribute to sustaining loneliness rather than offering a way out of it."
  ]
}